><span class="title">Personal Bio ::</span> <span class="value">The word Koji is an abbreviation of kabi-tacki meaning "bloom of mold". Koji is very important in Japan and like much of Japanese culture, was introduced from China approx. 200 A.D. From this "mother culture", many products are made, including Miso, Soy sauce, (Tamari or Shoyu), Amazake and Sake . Koji is mainly used as a starting process for producing these other culture-products. There are variations of koji which may employ different mixed strains of specific molds, yeast's or Lactic acid bacteria. These specific koji are prepared to suit the end product intended to be made. For best results, these products all need a tailored koji with specific enzyme activity. These enzymes mainly convert starches into simple fermentable sugars, so that in a possible second fermentation, the sugars become available for yeasts e.g., for preparing specific types of miso or sake. In addition, for miso production, proteins are converted into peptides (amino acids) by proteolytic enzymes (see below for a list of enzymes of koji).
[br]
Koji is prepared by steaming white short grain rice, barley or soybeans. Cooled to 35° C and inoculated with "tane koji" (seed of koji), an inoculum containing mainly mold spores of Aspergillus oryzae or A. sojae and possibly yeast and Lb. bacteria. The substrate is incubated for 3 to 4 days at approx. 42° C at 90 - 95% humidity. The koji is stirred during intervals throughout the incubation process, to reduce or eliminate excess heat from building up. This also helps the mold prolificate evenly through the entire rice. Lumps or clumps are also inhibited from forming. A white mycelium of new mold growth ofAspergillus oryzae should fully cover the rice. Koji is ready for harvest prior sporulation or maturation of the mold (when matured, the spores of this mold are pale Olive-green). This will ensure peak enzyme activity and good aroma. 
[br]
Koji contains high amounts of catalytic enzymes, including alpha-amylase (a starch to simple sugar converter), proteolytic enzymes, including protease's (3 types are known, one is active at acid, one at alkaline and one at neutral pH). Other enzymes include; sulfatases, nucleases, phosphatases, transglycosidases, peptidases, acylase, ribonucleo-depolymerase, mononucleotide phosphatase, adenyl-deaminases and purine nucleosidases. </span></div>	</div> 	<div id="contactinfo">		<h2>My Contact Information</h2>		<div id="email"><span class="title">Email Address ::</span> <span class="value"><a href="mailto:koji150@sciti.com">koji150@sciti.com</a></span> </div>		<div id="pm">		<span class="title">My Inbox ::</span> 				<span class="privatevalue">disabled</span>						</div>		<div id="im"><span class="title">IM ::</span> <span class="value">AOL - jcrKoji150</span></div>		<div id="link"><span class="title">Personal Link ::</span> <span class="value"><a href="http://www.koji150.cjb.net" target="_blank">My Personal Link</a></span></div>		<div id="recentposts"><span class="title">Recent Posts ::</span> 										<span class="value">		<dl>				<dt><a href="http://p084.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm19.showMessage?topicID=13759.topic&index=50" title="post" target="_blank">Re:</a></dt>		<dd><em>from <a href="http://p084.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm19" title="forum the above post is in" target="_blank">Member's Lounge</a></em></dd>				<dt><a href="http://p084.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm19.showMessage?topicID=13775.topic&index=7" title="post" target="_blank">Re:</a></dt>		<dd><em>from <a href="http://p084.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm19" title="forum the above post is in" target="_blank">Member's Lounge</a></em></dd>				<dt><a href="http://p084.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showMessage?topicID=1418.topic&index=10" title="post" target="_blank">Re:</a></dt>		<dd><em>from <a href="http://p084.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5" ti